The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	Calcutta: Former West Indies greats, Lance Gibbs and Clive Lloyd were inducted into the International Cricket Councils Hall of Fame during the lunch break of the first ODI between the West Indies and England at Guyana on Friday.     
	The cousins are two of the three Guyanese players to be inducted into the Hall of Fame, the third inductee being Rohan Kanhai who is due to receive his cap later in the year.         
	Calcutta: Cheteshwar Pujara said he was frightened following Wednesdays incident in Cuttack when two youths on a motorcycle forced themselves into the vehicle carrying him and West Zone cricketers Iqbal Abdulla and Bhavik Thaker. The trio were travelling to Bhubaneswar airport to catch a flight to Calcutta for a Kolkata Knight Riders camp. Pujara said he had informed his state association of the incident.        
	Calcutta: Jharkhand State Cricket Association president Amitabh Choudhary has been named manager for the India colts tour of Australia from April 3 to 22. The last time he was in a managerial post was during the senior teams controversial tour of Zimbabwe in September 2005.        
	Durban: The International Cricket Council (ICC) elite panel umpire Steve Bucknor, who, is officiating in his last Test in the match between Australia and South Africa in Cape Town, was honoured by the ICC Saturday.          
	Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) is in talks with its counterparts in England and Australia to arrange separate Test series against the two countries in England.          
	Zurich: Fifa will press ahead with plans to increase the number of home-grown players at clubs after a study said the idea was compatible with European law. The 6+5 proposal, where clubs would have to field six players eligible for their leagues national side, had stalled after European Union chiefs said it breached the blocs strict rules on free movement of workers.        
	Berlin: Every false starter in the sprints faces immediate exclusion from the race under a new proposal by the technical commission of the world governing body of athletics. Until now, one false start was allowed per race.        
	New Delhi: Top-seeds Rohan Bopanna and Aisam-ul Haq Qureshi went down fighting in straight sets to the third-seed Russian pair of Michail Elgin and Alexandre Kudryavtsev in the semi-final of the LTAT-SAT Bangkok Open ATP Challenger in Bangkok Saturday.    
